def unique_col_values(df):
    for column in df:
        print("{} | {} | {}".format(df[column].name, len(df[column].unique()),

In [7]:
responses = ['MALE', 'FEMALE']
temp_data = [33, 59]

explode = (0.1, 0.0)
colors = ("grey", "beige")
wp = {'linewidth':1, 'edgecolor':"green"}

def func(pct, allval):
    absolute = int(pct/100.*np.sum(allval))
    return "{:.1f}%\n({:d})".format(pct, absolute)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (10, 7))
wedges, texts, autotexts = ax.pie(temp_data,
                                  autopct = lambda pct: func(pct, temp_data),
                                  explode = explode,
                                  labels = responses,
                                  shadow = True,
                                  colors = colors,
                                  startangle = 90,
                                  wedgeprops = wp,
                                  textprops = dict(color = "BLACK"))

ax.legend(wedges, responses,
          title = "Responses",
          loc = "center left",
          bbox_to_anchor = (1, 0.5))
ax.set_title("GENDER PIE CHART")
plt.show()

It is observed from the outputs above that the Gender column consists of 33 (35.9%) males and 59 (64.1%) females.¶

df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Male': [17, 11, 3, 0],
    'Female': [51, 4, 6, 0]
 })

Class = ['18-23', '24-29', '30-35', '>=36']
ax = df.plot(stacked=True, kind='bar')

for bar in ax.patches:
    height = bar.get_height()
    width = bar.get_width()
    x = bar.get_x()
    y = bar.get_y()
    label_text = height
    label_x = x + width / 2
    label_y = y + height / 2
    ax.text(label_x, label_y, label_text, ha='center',    
            va='center')

ax.set_xticklabels(Class,rotation='horizontal')

plt.xlabel("Age group")
plt.ylabel("Frequency")

plt.show()

The outputs above tell us about the frequencies of respondents per age group and based on gender.¶
